3.19.20  9:58 pm   why does e flat major to g major sound so nice? specifically i'm talking about the last two measures of "bethena" by Scott Joplin. I'm not sure how to classify it so I can't search for information online. The particular voicing in Joplin's work just sounds so crisp and I'm not sure where that's coming from. Is it just the proximity to the g major triad in root position that gives it that effect and nothing else?

     you could spend your entire life trying to figure out why chords feel the way they do. i think i quarantined myself sometime in 2011 for about 2 weeks trying to find solid answers for things like this. but ultimately the answer to these things is usually what you already knew the first time you heard it

      I'm playing around with it in other keys and it's kind of rocking my socks. Have you used it before?

     yes of course. good trick to know
